🚀 1. Lambda Expression (Easy Explanation)
✅ What is Lambda?

A lambda expression is a short way to write a function (method) without creating a class or method explicitly.

👉 Think: “inline function”

🔹 Syntax
(parameters) -> { body }
🔹 Example (Before Lambda - Anonymous Class)
Runnable r = new Runnable() {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Running");
    }
};
🔹 Same using Lambda
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println("Running");
// No class, no override, very concise
🔹 Another Example
// Add two numbers
BiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;

System.out.println(add.apply(2, 3)); // 5
🧠 Key Points
Removes boilerplate code
Used with functional interfaces only
Improves readability
🚀 2. Functional Interface
✅ What is Functional Interface?

An interface with exactly ONE abstract method

@FunctionalInterface
interface MyInterface {
    void sayHello();  // Only one abstract method
}
🔹 Example with Lambda
MyInterface obj = () -> System.out.println("Hello");

obj.sayHello();
🧠 Key Points
Can have:
Multiple default methods
Multiple static methods
But only one abstract method
❗ Invalid Example
interface Test {
    void a();
    void b(); // ❌ Not functional interface (2 abstract methods)
}
🚀 3. Built-in Functional Interfaces (VERY IMPORTANT)

These are in java.util.function

🔹 1. Function<T, R>

👉 Takes input → returns output

Function<Integer, Integer> square = x -> x * x;

System.out.println(square.apply(5)); // 25
🔹 2. Predicate<T>

👉 Takes input → returns boolean

Predicate<Integer> isEven = x -> x % 2 == 0;

System.out.println(isEven.test(4)); // true
🔹 3. Consumer<T>

👉 Takes input → returns nothing

Consumer<String> print = s -> System.out.println(s);

print.accept("Hello");
🔹 4. Supplier<T>

👉 Takes no input → returns value

Supplier<Double> random = () -> Math.random();

System.out.println(random.get());
🔥 Summary Table
Interface	Input	Output
Function	Yes	Yes
Predicate	Yes	Boolean
Consumer	Yes	No
Supplier	No	Yes
🚀 4. Functional Programming (In Java)
✅ What is it?

A programming style where:

Functions are treated as first-class citizens
Focus on what to do, not how
🔹 Example (Imperative vs Functional)
❌ Traditional (Imperative)
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4,5);

for (int i : list) {
    if (i % 2 == 0) {
        System.out.println(i);
    }
}
✅ Functional (Using Lambda + Stream)
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x % 2 == 0) // condition
    .forEach(System.out::println); // action
🧠 Key Concepts
Immutability (avoid changing data)
Pure functions (same input → same output)
Declarative style
🚀 5. Important Interview Questions & Answers
🔥 Q1: What is a Lambda Expression?

👉 Answer:
A lambda expression is a concise way to represent a function using the syntax (args) -> body, mainly used to implement functional interfaces.

🔥 Q2: Why Lambda requires Functional Interface?

👉 Answer:
Because Java needs a target type to map the lambda to a method. Functional interface provides exactly one abstract method → no ambiguity.

🔥 Q3: Difference: Lambda vs Anonymous Class?
Feature	Lambda	Anonymous Class
Syntax	Short	Verbose
this keyword	Refers to outer class	Refers to inner class
Performance	Better	Slight overhead
🔥 Q4: Can Lambda access local variables?

👉 Yes, but only effectively final variables

int x = 10;

Runnable r = () -> {
    // x = 20; ❌ not allowed
    System.out.println(x); // ✅
};
🔥 Q5: What is “effectively final”?

👉 Variable whose value is not changed after initialization

🔥 Q6: What is Functional Interface?

👉 Interface with one abstract method, used as target for lambda expressions.

🔥 Q7: Can Functional Interface have multiple methods?

👉 Yes:

Only 1 abstract
Multiple default & static allowed
🔥 Q8: Difference: Function vs Predicate?

👉

Function → returns any type
Predicate → returns boolean
🔥 Q9: Why use Functional Programming?

👉 Benefits:

Cleaner code
Less bugs (immutability)
Better for parallel processing
🔥 Q10: Real-world usage?

👉 In:

Streams API
Event handling
Sorting (Comparator)
Filtering collections
🚀 6. Common Interview Traps

⚠️ They LOVE asking these:

Can lambda have multiple statements?
👉 Yes (use {})
(x) -> {
    System.out.println(x);
    return x * 2;
}
Can we throw checked exception in lambda?
👉 Not directly (needs handling)
Can we create our own functional interface?
👉 Yes (very common in interviews)
